[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is it possible to use <code>#[test]</code> in a driver? I have tried adding this to one of the source files of nova-core, and it even fails to fail at build time:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"cp\">#[cfg(test)]</span>\n<span class=\"k\">mod</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nn\">tests</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">use</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">kernel</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">prelude</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"cp\">#[test]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">test_foo</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">build_assert</span><span class=\"o\">!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"kc\">false</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p><code>make LLVM=1 rusttest</code> simply ignores this test, even if the driver is built-in. Am I missing something?</p>",
        "id": 520349341,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748227953
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>rusttest</code> is the target for host test, and I'm not sure whether the <code>#[test]</code> works for that. We usually care more about kunit, that's is if you run <code>kunit.py</code> or build with <code>CONFIG_KUNIT</code>.</p>",
        "id": 520350913,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748229211
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yup, I am aware that the tests would run on the host and that's precisely what I want in this case :)</p>",
        "id": 520351006,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748229282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>then I think you need to <code>CONFIG_KUNIT=y</code></p>",
        "id": 520351203,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748229450
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, I mis-read</p>",
        "id": 520351266,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748229487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you're using <code>#[cfg(tests)]</code></p>",
        "id": 520351297,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748229524
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>then I don't know why it doesn't work :)</p>",
        "id": 520351307,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748229539
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hehe. Thanks anyway! :)</p>",
        "id": 520351408,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748229613
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I usually just use kunit, host tests are hard to use anyway.</p>",
        "id": 520351479,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748229711
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like how little friction there is in running the host tests with your <code>.config</code>. KUnit tests are nice but running <code>kunit.py</code> with the right additional options can be tricky (and requires a <code>make mrproper</code>)</p>",
        "id": 520351595,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748229816
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also it's harder to type them as rustdoc :P</p>",
        "id": 520351616,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748229840
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We have the new <code>#[kunit_tests(name)]</code> macro now</p>",
        "id": 520351866,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748230046
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so you don't need to write a rustdoc for a test (still should provide examples for public functions, but tests can be written in different ways).</p>",
        "id": 520351972,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1748230112
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>#[kunit_tests]</code> indeed looks useful to write doctests more comfortably before moving them to their final destination</p>",
        "id": 520354559,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748232036
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the rusttest target is a manual enumeration of crates in the build system; that's my guess as to why it doesn't work in a driver</p>",
        "id": 520420146,
        "sender_full_name": "Tamir Duberstein",
        "timestamp": 1748257204
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed, looking at <code>rust/Makefile</code> that appears to be the case:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Makefile\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nf\">rusttest</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rusttest</span>-<span class=\"n\">macros</span> <span class=\"n\">rusttest</span>-<span class=\"n\">kernel</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 520580932,
        "sender_full_name": "Alexandre Courbot",
        "timestamp": 1748323426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I plan to add support for other crates for all the usual \"special\" features we have for <code>kernel</code> etc., but it is not there yet.</p>",
        "id": 520611363,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1748335141
    }
]